Since $BD = DE = EC,$ triangle $ABC$ is isosceles.  Therefore, $\angle ABC = \angle ACB.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E;

A = dir(135);
B = dir(210);
C = dir(335);
D = (B + C)/2;
E = extension(A, B, C, D);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);
draw(B--E);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, W);
label("$C$", C, NE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, S);
[/asy]

Then $\angle A = \angle B = \angle C,$ so $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = \angle A,$ which means triangle $ABC$ is isosceles.  Hence, $\sin (x + y) = \sin (y + z).$

By the Law of Sines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{AB}{\sin A} = \frac{AC}{\sin C}.\]Since $\angle A = \angle B = \angle C,$ $\sin A = \sin B = \sin C,$ so
\[\frac{AB}{\sin A} = \frac{AB}{\sin A} = \frac{AC}{\sin C}.\]Hence, $AB = AC,$ so $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles.

Let $a = BC.$  Then $BD = DE = EC = a,$ so $x = y = z = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \angle BAD.$

Also, by the Law of Sines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{AB}{\sin A} = \frac{AC}{\sin C}.\]Since $\angle A = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \angle BAD,$ $\sin A = \sin \left( \frac{1}{2} \cdot \angle BAD \right) = \frac{1}{2} \sin \angle BAD.$  Then
\[\frac{AB}{\sin A} = \frac{AB}{\frac{1}{2} \sin \angle BAD} = 2 \sin \angle BAD.\]Since $\angle BAD$ is acute, $\sin \angle BAD < 1,$ so
\[\frac{AB}{\sin A} = 2 \sin \angle BAD < 2.\]Then $\sin \angle BAD < \frac{1}{2}.$  But then $\angle BAD < \frac{\pi}{3},$ which means $\angle BAD = \frac{\pi}{3}.$  Hence,
\[\frac{\sin (x + y) \sin (y + z)}{\sin x \sin z} = \boxed{2}.\]

