Note that $9^{t+1} = 9^t \cdot 9 = 9 \cdot 9^t$. We can then rewrite the equation as follows: \begin{align*}
3 \cdot 3^t + \sqrt{9 \cdot 9^t} &= 18\\
3 \cdot 3^t + \sqrt{9} \cdot 3^{2t} &= 18\\
3 \cdot 3^t + 3^{2t} &= 18
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the fact that $a^2 - b^2 = (a+b)(a-b)$ to factor the equation as follows: \begin{align*}
3 \cdot 3^t + 3^{2t} &= 18\\
(3^t + 3^{2t}) \cdot 3 &= 18\\
3 \cdot (3^t + 3^{2t}) &= 18\\
3 \cdot \text{(some value)} &= 18\\
\text{(some value)} &= 6
\end{align*}

Therefore, $3^t + 3^{2t} = 6$. We can then substitute $3^t = a$ and $3^{2t} = b$: \begin{align*}
a + b &= 6\\
3a + 9b &= 6
\end{align*}

We can then use the fact that $a^2 - b^2 = (a+b)(a-b)$ to factor the equation as follows: \begin{align*}
3a + 9b &= 6\\
(3a + 9b) \cdot 1 &= 6\\
3(a + 3b) &= 6\\
3 \cdot \text{(some value)} &= 6\\
\text{(some value)} &= 2
\end{align*}

Therefore, $a + 3b = 2$. We can then substitute $3b = 2 - a$ into the equation $a + 3b = 2$: \begin{align*}
a + 3b &= 2\\
a + 3(2 - a) &= 2\\
a + 6 - 3a &= 2\\
6 - 2 &= 3a\\
4 &= 3a\\
\frac{4}{3} &= a
\end{align*}

Therefore, $a = \frac{4}{3}$. Substituting $a = \frac{4}{3}$ into $a + 3b = 2$, we find that $3b = 2 - \frac{4}{3} = \frac{2}{3}$. Therefore, $b = \frac{2}{9}$.

Therefore, $3^t + 3^{2t} = 6$ when $t = \boxed{\frac{2}{3}}$.

