The line $y = -x + 1$ is parallel to the $x$-axis and has slope $-1,$ so it intersects the $xz$-plane at $(0,1,0).$  Similarly, the line $z = -2x + 1$ is parallel to the $y$-axis and has slope $-2,$ so it intersects the $xy$-plane at $(1,0,-2).$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair P, Q;

P = (1,1/3);
Q = (0,1/3);

draw((-1,0)--(5,0));
draw((0,-1)--(0,3));
draw((0,0)--(1,0));
draw((0,0)--(0,1));
draw(P--(P + 2*dir(120))--(P + 2*dir(-60)),dashed);
draw(Q--(Q + 2*dir(120))--(Q + 2*dir(-60)),dashed);

dot("$P$", P, NW);
dot("$Q$", Q, NE);
[/asy]

We want to find the intersection of the line segment $\overline{PQ}$ with the planes $x = 0,$ $y = 0,$ and $z = 0.$  This is the intersection of the hyperplane $x = 0$ with the planes $y = -x + 1,$ $z = -2x + 1,$ and $z = -2x + 1,$ which is the hyperplane $y = -x + 1.$

Thus, the smallest possible value of $PQ$ is $\boxed{1}.$

